<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33928" authority="Emery" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole piceonigra Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceonigra">Pheidole piceonigra Emery</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="nomenclature">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">Types Naturhist. Mus. Wien (unde rpicea Mayr).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33928" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole piceonigra Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceonigra">piceonigra</taxonomicName>
, pitch-black plus black.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
Diagnosis Close to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
of Costa Rica, considered by Longino (1997) to belong with it in a single, very variable species. The types, however, are very different, with those of 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33928" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole piceonigra Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceonigra">piceonigra</taxonomicName>
distinguished as follows.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
Major: 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33928" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole piceonigra Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceonigra">piceonigra</taxonomicName>
with much less abundant pilosity than 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
; rugoreticulation between eye and antennal fossa; color much darker (see Color below), and head concolorous, not bicolorous as in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
; posterior side of head with bands of foveolae; humerus in dorsal-oblique view rounded; apex of postpetiole in side view more rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
Minor: occiput and posterior sides of head foveolate, not smooth as in 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
; much less pilose than 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
; color much lighter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="216">If continuous intergrades are demonstrated between the two forms, they may be joined; otherwise it is more prudent to distinguish them as species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="216">Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 1.06, HL 1.04, SL 0.76, EL 0.20, PW 0.54. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.62, HL 0.70, SL 0.80, EL 0.14, PW 0.40. Color Major: body dark brown, gaster almost black.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="216">Minor: head, mesosoma, and waist dark reddish brown; propodeum and gaster blackish brown; appendages medium brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
Range I have seen series from Chiapas, Tamaulipas, and Veracruz in Mexico, at 1070-2200 m, and from Costa Rica. On the basis of the types, I am considering this species as different from 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
, which also occurs in Costa Rica.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="216">
Biology Longino's notes (1997) on the distribution and natural history of &quot; 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33799" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole indistincta Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indistincta">indistincta</taxonomicName>
&quot; may apply to that species, to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33928" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole piceonigra Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceonigra">piceonigra</taxonomicName>
, or to both. I found a large, undoubted 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33928" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole piceonigra Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="216" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="piceonigra">piceonigra</taxonomicName>
colony nesting at the base of an ornamental shrub in a much disturbed San Jose city park. In Tamaulipas, the Cornell University Mexico Field Party of 1965 encountered it at 1070 m in tall cloud forest.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
